AGI - It is on 30 May 2022, Maurizio Cocco>, who from just under a year and a half moved to Ivory Coast, receives a phone call as many arrive in those days on his mobile phone. He was able to move in the chaotic capital Abidjan> and although his activity is not yet taken off, he is optimistic. At age 59 he has a solid experience in the field of construction and knows that the Ivory Coast is one of the many African countries that need infrastructure. He, who for 12 years worked for the Caltagirone group>, created the Casal Boccone area in Rome and the entire TIM building in via della Magliana, is convinced to be the right person in the right place.
<h2> Arrest and charges
Calling it on the phone is a general who Cocco knows well: it is one of the most elegant frequenters of the Abidjan> restaurant, located right under his apartment. There are politicians, diplomats, businessmen and apparatus: the kind of local you have to attend to enter the tour that matters. With one of the owners Cocco has also constituted for a few months a society of construction.<br> The general, to whom Cocco has supplied regularly paid building materials, waits under the house and kindly invites him to get in the car. In the car there are also some military, but Cocco is not surprising: "The general was always with the escort," he says. They talk about work, but at some point the high officer stops the car, goes down and asks Cocco to follow his colleagues for control.
It is the beginning of a nightmare that is not yet finished.&nbsp;Maurizio Cocco is arrested > and three days after he is challenged the accusations of international traffic of narcotics, association to delinquere and percosse>. Along with him, 65 other people have been arrested in what the local press describes as the most important operation against crime in the history of the country. In prison also ends a relative of the managers of the restaurant - the chef - that Cocco attends and that, we said, is located right under his apartment, another Italian manages to escape in Lebanon.&nbsp;
<h2> Testing and defence
Ivorian pollutants suspect Cocco is an accomplice to some Spanish and Colombian citizens: their phones hook the same cell on three occasions: 13 February 2022, 11 March 2022 and 15 April 2022. It is a pity that his office was close to the area frequented by drug dealers > and that, on March 11, 2022, the engineer had gone to a small hotel - La Pergola - of that area to pay the bill to two Italian workers who had reached it in the African country for some work in the only yard that at that time had and that on April 15 of the same year the Engineer had returned to Italy for Easter surprise.
<div </div
&nbsp;
Before going to jail, in a cell of 50 square meters in which 220 people are locked up, he made time to warn the wife who immediately left and, as soon as she arrived, he was looking for a lawyer. But there is no way to convince the judges to grant at least domiciliar arrests to the Italian engineer, despite Spanish and Colombian drug dealers >– all sentenced to twenty years – they have in the course of the process categorically excluded having entertained any relationship with Cocco>.<br> Meanwhile, one of the Calabrian owners of the restaurant – the one with which the engineer had formed the company – is arrested and extradited in Italy, where he has to pay a sentence to twelve years in prison.
<h2> The role of Italian diplomacy
The machine of justice and Italian diplomacy has moved quickly for him, but not as fast as it seems to have for Cocco, who remains in prison > despite the charges charged to him have fallen. To keep it in the cell is another dispute, that of recycling that would result from a payment received from a well-known Italian-French entrepreneur who with him collaborated in the only yard. A story of which no further details are known today. &nbsp;<br> Ivorian justice is slow and Cocco passes into detention more than two years.> So much so that when the first-degree sentence is issued to two years for tax fraud, in fact it has already discounted them. It is on May 7, 2024 and on the track, in Ciampino, there is a plane waiting to leave at the time of Abidjan to bring him home. But, says lawyer Mario Cicchetti, who in the meantime took over in the management of the case, there is some hitch and the operation is aborted. In addition, the Ivorian lawyers of Cocco filed an appeal against the judgment – their goal is to clarify the innocence of the enegner>e – and local justice has relaunched with a charge of recycling that still holds it in prison, waiting for the sentence of a process that is still under investigation and that no one has any idea how long it will last.
<h2> Health condition
“In the meantime, Cocco lost half of his weight,” says Cicchetti, “has contracted malaria and a quantity of viruses > that we don’t even know in Europe and had a stroke. In April 2024 Mattarella was in Ivory Coast and was undoubtedly aware of Cocco's situation.
<div </div
&nbsp;
Antonio Tajani himself is also aware of this because he is native to Fiuggi, just like the engineer. If the Italian authorities do not do what they have to and have already done for other compatriots in such conditions, they will have his life on their conscience, whether he is guilty or not. The very serious health situation in which it is found is seriously jeopardized by the unacceptable conditions of detention, which do not guarantee its survival".
<h2> A hope &nbsp; di&nbsp; freedom</h2>
But isn't Italian diplomacy moving or not doing enough, as Cicchetti denounces? “From the beginning, the Italian embassy in Abidjan>, in close connection with the Farnesina, has followed the story with the utmost attention” is the answer that comes from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, “with every necessary assistance to Cocco and his family, carrying out consular visits in the penitentiary of Abidjan, and raising the ivorian authorities on the case, in the limits of independence and autonomy. The embassy has already formally requested authorization to make as soon as possible a new consular visit > and remains pending a reply from the Ivorian authorities. It is not possible to ask, as happened in other situations, that Cocco discounts a possible penalty in Italy because it is the appeal against the sentence of first degree and the process for recycling are still pending.
<div </div
&nbsp;
In the meantime, he still tells the lawyer, a sort of cow market was held on the possibility of a bail> that at first had been fixed to one and a half million euros > and in three months, by means of bargaining, seems to be dropped to 150 thousand euros >. A light, however filthy, lit at the bottom of the tunnel and Cocco could soon leave the prison of Abidjan and wait for the times of ivorian justice in the house, even if now enthralled in the physical and spirit and in ruin. “This is why we must return it to Italy as soon as possible,” concludes the lawyer who yesterday asked for an urgent meeting with Prime Minister Meloni and Minister&nbsp; Tajani.
